### Implementation 1: First Fit Decreasing (FFD)

This implementation prioritizes bins that can fit the item, with higher capacity remaining.

def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:
    remaining_capacity = bins - item
    remaining_capacity[remaining_capacity < 0] = -1  # Mark bins that can't fit the item
    priority_scores = np.where(remaining_capacity > 0, remaining_capacity, 0)
    return priority_scores

### Implementation 2: Best Fit Decreasing (BFD)

This implementation places the item in the bin with the smallest excess capacity.

def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:
    remaining_capacity = bins - item
    remaining_capacity[remaining_capacity < 0] = np.inf  # Mark bins that can't fit the item
    priority_scores = np.where(remaining_capacity > 0, np.abs(remaining_capacity - 0), np.inf)
    return priority_scores

### Implementation 3: Worst Fit (WF)

This implementation places the item in the bin with the largest remaining capacity.

def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:
    remaining_capacity = bins - item
    remaining_capacity[remaining_capacity < 0] = -1  # Mark bins that can't fit the item
    priority_scores = np.where(remaining_capacity > 0, remaining_capacity, 0)
    return priority_scores

### Implementation 4: Greedy by Bin Utilization

This implementation prioritizes bins with the least space used.

def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:
    utilization = bins / (bins + item)
    priority_scores = np.where(bins >= item, utilization, 0)
    return priority_scores

### Implementation 5: Least Load

This implementation prioritizes bins with the least total load.

